'''Kalyn Heffernan''' is an MC for the [[Krip Hop]] band Wheelchair Sports Camp.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://wheelchairsportscamp.co/bio|title=Wheelchair Sports Camp|last=Wheelchair Sports Camp|first=|date=2018|work=|access-date=August 18, 2018}}</ref> Heffernan was born with the genetic disorder [[osteogenesis imperfecta]]. She was born in [[Denver]], spent her early life in Southern California,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/01/09/wheelchair-sports-camp-em_n_1194427.html|title=Wheelchair Sports Camp: Kalyn Heffernan on Hip Hop, Occupy Denver|last=Ferner|first=Matt|date=December 6, 2017|work=Huffington Post|access-date=August 19, 2018}}</ref> and returned to Denver at age 10.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.denverpost.com/2011/04/12/world-is-spinning-big-time-for-little-mc-in-colorado/|title=World is Spinning Big Time for Little MC in Colorado|last=Baca|first=Ricardo|date=April 12, 2011|work=Denver Post|access-date=August 18, 2018}}</ref> Heffernan is a community activist, participating in a 2017 [[ADAPT]] sit-in at Senator [[Cory Gardner]]'s office to protest a proposed healthcare bill that would have cut [[Medicaid]] by $722 billion. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.westword.com/music/wheelchair-sports-camps-kalyn-heffernan-on-arrest-with-adapt-at-cory-gardners-office-9228638|title=Wheelchair Sports Camp's Kalyn Heffernan on Arrest with Adapt at Cory Gardner's Office|last=Harris|first=Kyle|date=July 5, 2017|website=Westword|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=August 18, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.esquire.com/news-politics/news/a56038/kalyn-heffernan-cory-gardner-healthcare-protest-denver/|title=55 Hours in a Republican Senator's Office, Defending Our Right to Live|last=Miller|first=Matt|date=June 29, 2017|work=Esquire|access-date=August 19, 2018}}</ref> In 2018, Heffernan announced her intention to "sit" as a candidate for the 2019 Denver mayoral race.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.westword.com/news/wheelchair-sports-camps-kalyn-heffernan-is-running-for-mayor-of-denver-10153628|title=Wheelchair Sports Camp's Kalyn Heffernan is Running for Mayor of Denver|last=Campbell|first=Ana|date=April 1, 2018|work=Westword|access-date=August 18, 2018}}</ref>
Heffernan identifies as queer, and was named as one of "Eight Openly Queer Rappers to Watch" by ''[[ColorLines|Colorlines]].''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.colorlines.com/articles/eight-openly-queer-rappers-worth-your-headphones|title=Eight Openly Queer Rappers Worth Your Headphones|last=King|first=Jamilah|date=May 11, 2011|work=Colorlines|access-date=August 19, 2018}}</ref> She received a 2016 ''[[Westword]]'' MasterMind award in recognition of her work co-founding Royalty Free Haiti, a partnership between artists in Haiti and Denver<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.westword.com/news/meet-our-latest-masterminds-kalyn-heffernan-and-birdseed-collective-6819315|title=Meet Our Latest Masterminds Kalyn Heffernan and Birdseed Collective|last=Froyd|first=Susan|date=June 15, 2018|work=Westword|access-date=August 18, 2018}}</ref> and in 2018, ''Westword''<nowiki/>'s "Best of Denver" named her the year's "Best Activist Musician."<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.westword.com/best-of/2018/arts-and-entertainment/best-activist-musician-10133734|title=Best of Denver: Best Activist Musician {{!}} Kalyn Heffernan|last=Westword|first=|date=2018|work=Westword|access-date=August 19, 2018}}</ref> == References == <references /> {{DEFAULTSORT:Heffernan, Kalyn}}
