{{distinguish|The Sirens and Ulysses}} {{Infobox artwork | title = Ulysses and the Sirens | painting_alignment = | other_language_1 = | other_title_1 = | other_language_2 = | other_title_2 = | image_file = Ulysses and the Sirens by H.J. Draper.jpg | image_size = | alt = A painting of a boat in which several men are rowing while another man is tied to the mast and three mermaids are in the process of boarding the ship and losing their tails | caption = | artist = [[Herbert James Draper]] | catalogue = | year = {{start date|1909}} | completion_date = <!-- For a more specific date (post-1583): {{start date|YYYY|MM|DD|df=y}} --> | material = [[Oil painting|Oil on canvas]] | subject = A scene from [[Homer]]'s ''[[Odyssey]]'' in which [[Odysseus|Ulysses]] is tormented by [[Siren (mythology)|Sirens]] | height_metric = <!-- (i.e. in metric units) --> | width_metric = | length_metric = | diameter_metric = | height_imperial = 69.25 <!-- (i.e. in imperial units) --> | width_imperial = 84 | length_imperial = | diameter_imperial = | dimensions = | dimensions_ref = | metric_unit = cm <!-- Note: this parameter must either use the value given or not be included --> | imperial_unit = in <!-- Note: this parameter must either use the value given or not be included --> | condition = | city = [[Kingston upon Hull]] | museum = [[Ferens Art Gallery]] | accession = | coordinates = <!-- Only use for the coordinates (when known) of the artwork itself, i.e. not for the site, building, structure, etc where it is kept, otherwise leave blank (or omit): {{coord|LAT|LON|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} --> | owner = | url = [http://www.hullcc.gov.uk/museumcollections/collections/storydetail.php?irn=145 www.hullcc.gov.uk] }} '''''Ulysses and the Sirens''''' is a 1909 [[oil painting]] by [[Herbert James Draper]] measuring 69.25 x 84 in.{{sfn|Menges|2009|p=56}} It is held at the [[Ferens Art Gallery]] in [[Kingston upon Hull]], England.{{sfn|Impelluso & Zuffi|2003|p=293}} The gallery purchased the painting from Draper in 1910 for £600.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Ulysses and the Sirens|publisher=Hull City Council|url=http://www.hullcc.gov.uk/museumcollections/collections/storydetail.php?irn=145|accessdate=August 30, 2015}}</ref> Draper also painted a reduced [[replica]] that is housed at the [[Leeds Art Gallery]].{{sfn|Robertson et al.|2007|p=20}} The subject of the painting is an episode in the [[Epic poetry|epic poem]] ''[[Odyssey]]'' by [[Homer]] in which [[Odysseus|Ulysses]] is tormented by the voices of [[Siren (mythology)|Sirens]], although there are only two Sirens in Homer's poem and they stay in a meadow.{{sfn|Scott|2006|p=107}} The painting depicts Ulysses tied to the [[Mast (sailing)|mast]] and forcibly attendant to the Sirens' seductions.<ref>{{Cite journal|journal=[[Neurosurgery (journal)|Neurosurgery]]|title=Ulysses and the Sirens by Herbert James Draper (1863–1920)|author=Salcman, Michael|date=August 2006|volume=59|issue=2|page=422}}</ref> Although the Sirens were depicted in [[ancient Greek art]] as scary, ugly creatures, Draper maintains the spirit but not the content of the story by transferring the Sirens' seductiveness from their song to a visible form, depicting the Sirens as beautiful [[mermaid]]s who invade Ulysses' ship.{{sfn|Baker & Christensen|2013|p=210}} The Sirens are [[Nude (art)|nude]] and their tails disappear as they board the ship.{{sfn|Robinson|2007|p=439}} Draper's conflation of Sirens with mermaids and his [[sexualization]] of these figures are consistent with other artwork of the [[Victorian era|Victorian]] and [[Edwardian era]]s.{{sfn|Sax|2013|p=94}} Norwegian social theorist [[Jon Elster]] used the name of Draper's painting as the title for his 1979 book about [[rationality]] and [[precommitment]].{{sfn|Halvorsen|2014|p=281}}
