{{italic title}} [[File:WinterTrees.jpg|thumb|First edition (publ. [[Faber & Faber]])]] '''''Winter Trees''''' is a 1971 posthumous collection of poetry by [[Sylvia Plath]], published by her husband [[Ted Hughes]].<ref name="Badia2011">{{cite book|author=Janet Badia|title=Sylvia Plath and the Mythology of Women Readers|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_CxXQ1G1btwC&pg=PA189|year=2011|publisher=Univ of Massachusetts Press|isbn=1-55849-896-6|pages=189–190}}</ref><ref name="Kirk2004">{{cite book|author=Connie Ann Kirk|title=Sylvia Plath: A Biography|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NBlJYGHVESwC&pg=PR21|date=1 January 2004|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-313-33214-2|pages=xx–xxi}}</ref> Along with ''[[Crossing the Water]]'' it provides the remainder of the poems that Plath had written during her state of elevated creativity prior to her suicide.<ref name="Gill2008">{{cite book|author=Jo Gill|title=The Cambridge Introduction to Sylvia Plath|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nUv88oFidOoC&pg=PA12|date=11 September 2008|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-1-139-47413-9|page=12}}</ref>
